## Set up React Hook Form with Zod validation

### 1. Install dependencies
```
npm install react-hook-form @hookform/resolvers zod
```
- `react-hook-form` — the form library (uncontrolled, performant)
- `@hookform/resolvers` — connects Zod schemas to React Hook Form
- `zod` — schema validation (may already be installed)

### 2. Define a Zod schema
- Create schemas in `lib/schemas/` for reuse across client and server:
  ```ts
  // lib/schemas/contact.ts
  import { z } from 'zod';

  export const contactSchema = z.object({
    name: z.string().min(2, 'Name must be at least 2 characters'),
    email: z.string().email('Please enter a valid email'),
    message: z.string().min(10, 'Message must be at least 10 characters').max(500),
    role: z.enum(['user', 'admin', 'guest']).default('user'),
  });

  export type ContactFormData = z.infer<typeof contactSchema>;
  ```
- `z.infer<typeof schema>` generates the TypeScript type from the schema automatically.

### 3. Build a validated form component
  ```tsx
  'use client';
  import { useForm } from 'react-hook-form';
  import { zodResolver } from '@hookform/resolvers/zod';
  import { contactSchema, type ContactFormData } from '@/lib/schemas/contact';

  export function ContactForm() {
    const {
      register,
      handleSubmit,
      formState: { errors, isSubmitting },
      reset,
    } = useForm<ContactFormData>({
      resolver: zodResolver(contactSchema),
      defaultValues: { role: 'user' },
    });

    const onSubmit = async (data: ContactFormData) => {
      await fetch('/api/contact', {
        method: 'POST',
        body: JSON.stringify(data),
      });
      reset();
    };

    return (
      <form onSubmit={handleSubmit(onSubmit)} noValidate>
        <div>
          <label htmlFor="name">Name</label>
          <input id="name" {...register('name')} />
          {errors.name && <p role="alert">{errors.name.message}</p>}
        </div>

        <div>
          <label htmlFor="email">Email</label>
          <input id="email" type="email" {...register('email')} />
          {errors.email && <p role="alert">{errors.email.message}</p>}
        </div>

        <div>
          <label htmlFor="message">Message</label>
          <textarea id="message" {...register('message')} />
          {errors.message && <p role="alert">{errors.message.message}</p>}
        </div>

        <button type="submit" disabled={isSubmitting}>
          {isSubmitting ? 'Sending...' : 'Send'}
        </button>
      </form>
    );
  }
  ```
- `handleSubmit` only calls `onSubmit` when all validation passes.
- `noValidate` disables browser native validation so Zod handles it.
- Always add `role="alert"` to error messages for screen reader accessibility.

### 4. Validate on the server too
- Never trust client-only validation. Re-validate in API routes or Server Actions:
  ```ts
  // app/api/contact/route.ts
  import { NextRequest, NextResponse } from 'next/server';
  import { contactSchema } from '@/lib/schemas/contact';

  export async function POST(req: NextRequest) {
    const body = await req.json();
    const result = contactSchema.safeParse(body);

    if (!result.success) {
      return NextResponse.json(
        { errors: result.error.flatten().fieldErrors },
        { status: 400 }
      );
    }

    const { name, email, message } = result.data;
    // process safely...
    return NextResponse.json({ success: true });
  }
  ```
- `safeParse` returns `{ success: true, data }` on success or `{ success: false, error }` on failure.
- `error.flatten().fieldErrors` maps errors to field names for structured client display.

### 5. Use with Server Actions
  ```tsx
  'use client';
  import { useForm } from 'react-hook-form';
  import { zodResolver } from '@hookform/resolvers/zod';
  import { contactSchema, type ContactFormData } from '@/lib/schemas/contact';
  import { submitContact } from '@/app/actions/contact';

  export function ContactForm() {
    const { register, handleSubmit, formState: { errors } } = useForm<ContactFormData>({
      resolver: zodResolver(contactSchema),
    });

    return (
      <form onSubmit={handleSubmit(async (data) => {
        const result = await submitContact(data);
        if (!result.success) console.error(result.errors);
      })}>
        {/* fields */}
      </form>
    );
  }
  ```
  ```ts
  // app/actions/contact.ts
  'use server';
  import { contactSchema } from '@/lib/schemas/contact';

  export async function submitContact(data: unknown) {
    const result = contactSchema.safeParse(data);
    if (!result.success) return { success: false, errors: result.error.flatten().fieldErrors };
    // save to database...
    return { success: true };
  }
  ```

### 6. Controlled inputs (Select, Checkbox, Date pickers)
- Use `Controller` for UI library components that don't forward a ref:
  ```tsx
  import { Controller } from 'react-hook-form';

  <Controller
    control={control}
    name="role"
    render={({ field }) => (
      <select {...field}>
        <option value="user">User</option>
        <option value="admin">Admin</option>
      </select>
    )}
  />
  ```
- Use `Controller` for: `<select>`, checkboxes, date pickers, shadcn Select/Combobox.
- Use `register` for standard `<input>` and `<textarea>` elements.

### 7. Dynamic field arrays
  ```tsx
  import { useFieldArray } from 'react-hook-form';

  const { fields, append, remove } = useFieldArray({ control, name: 'items' });

  return (
    <>
      {fields.map((field, index) => (
        <div key={field.id}>
          <input {...register(`items.${index}.value`)} />
          <button type="button" onClick={() => remove(index)}>Remove</button>
        </div>
      ))}
      <button type="button" onClick={() => append({ value: '' })}>Add item</button>
    </>
  );
  ```
- Always use `field.id` (not the index) as the React `key` to avoid reconciliation issues.

### Common errors & fixes
- **`Resolver returned values that do not exist in schema`** → The Zod field names don't match `register()` names. Check spelling.
- **`Cannot read properties of undefined (reading 'message')`** → You're reading `errors.field.message` but the field isn't in the schema. Add it to the Zod object.
- **Form submits without validation** → You forgot `handleSubmit`. Wrap: `<form onSubmit={handleSubmit(yourHandler)}`.
- **Input value doesn't reset after submit** → Call `reset()` after submission. It clears all fields to `defaultValues`.
- **Select or custom component not validated** → Use `Controller` instead of `register` for non-native elements.
- **TypeScript: `data` is `any` in `onSubmit`** → Add the generic: `useForm<ContactFormData>({ resolver: zodResolver(schema) })`.
- **`isSubmitting` stays `true` after an error** → The `onSubmit` function threw an unhandled error. Wrap in try/catch.

### What NOT to do
- Do NOT validate only on the client. Always re-validate on the server with the same Zod schema.
- Do NOT use `useState` to track form field values — let React Hook Form manage state. It avoids unnecessary re-renders.
- Do NOT call `e.preventDefault()` inside `handleSubmit` — it already handles that.
- Do NOT define schemas inline inside the component — put them in `lib/schemas/` to share with server-side validation.
- Do NOT call `watch()` on every field if you only need one — `watch('fieldName')` is more performant than watching all fields.
- Do NOT ignore `formState.errors` — always display errors next to the relevant input field.
- Do NOT use array index as `key` in `useFieldArray` — use `field.id` to preserve input identity across re-renders.
